Exploratory Data Analysis on Amazon Kindle Book Sales

Agomuo Kelechi

Exploratory Data Analysis of Amazon Kindle Books

Sales is the most important aspect of any business; thus, all businesses need to pay attention to their sales data.

Sales data is any information that is human and machine-readable and is useful to sales teams and the organization. It aids in decision-making, greater client comprehension, and enhancing future performance within the organization.

Sales data can provide insightful information about a sales team’s effectiveness, and aid in the creation of better strategies. It can also,

  • Help improve organizational decision-making,

  • Provide actionable information about a sales team’s performance,

  • Assist sales representatives in avoiding pursuing customers who are a bad fit, and

  • Inform new opportunities that sales teams wouldn’t otherwise detect, and assist in forecasting future sales.

Sales data should therefore not be neglected by any business or organization. In this report, I performed an exploratory data analysis on Amazon Kindle Books.

Objectives

The objectives include to:

  • Determine the most popular authors based on the number of books they have released and their ratings.

  • Investigate the influence of Kindle Unlimited on book sales and popularity.

  • Assess the impact of the “Best Seller” and “Editors’ Pick” tags on book sales.

  • Examine book publication trends over time and look for seasonal patterns.

  • Learn about the sales and popularity of kindle books based on their categories.

#Let's check summary of each column with duplicates by summarizing each column
#I'll use a for look to iterate through each column in the table

# Firstly, let's create an empty list to store the summary tables
dupTables <- list()
# Let's use the for loop to iterate through each column in the salesData
for (col_name in names(salesData)) {
  # Create a summary table for the current column
  summaryTable <- salesData %>%
    group_by(!!sym(col_name)) %>%
    summarise(Count = n()) %>%
    filter(Count > 1) %>% 
    arrange(desc(Count))
  
  # Store the summary table in the list with the column name as the list name
  dupTables[[col_name]] <- summaryTable
}

On the other hand, if we want to input all 55302 missing data, we may introduce bias in our analysis which could lead to misleading results.

Looking at the variables, you should understand that author and soldBy variables are critical to our analysis. What I would do is to remove all observations that has missing values in author and soldBy columns.

For our publishedDate variable, we can input random dates between the already existing date interval.

Dealing with missing data

Firstly, let us remove the rows that coincide with all the missing variables.

#Rows with 3 of the missing variables: author, soldBy and publishedDate
missing_var <- subset(salesData, author == "Not Available" & 
                         soldBy == "Not Available" & 
                         publishedDate == "0001-01-01")
head(missing_var)

This gave us 31 observations that do not have author, soldBy and publishedDate. Thus, we remove these rows and have a total of 133071 left.

Let’s now remove those 31 observations from our data set. We have a new data set called salesData_rev.

salesData_rev <- subset(salesData, author !="Not Available" |
                          soldBy != "Not Available" |
                          publishedDate != "0001-01-01")
head(salesData_rev)

Secondly, let’s remove all rows that have missing authors. But how many authors are missing in our data?

author_NA <- salesData_rev %>% 
  filter(author == "Not Available") %>% 
  select(asin, author)
str(author_NA)

So, 393 authors are missing. Let’s remove these rows from our data.

#Let's remove the rows where author is not aavailable
salesData_rev <- subset(salesData_rev, author != "Not Available")

#Let's be sure that all NA authors have been removed
head(subset(salesData_rev, author == "Not Available" | author == "NA"))

Thirdly, we’ll remove all rows that have missing soldBy data.

#How many rows do not have soldBy data
soldBy_NA <- subset(salesData_rev, soldBy == "Not Available")
#Remove the missing data from the data set
salesData_rev <- subset(salesData_rev, soldBy != "Not Available")
#check to be sure we've removed all NA
head(subset(salesData_rev, soldBy == "Not Available" | soldBy == "NA"))

Now, we have a total of 123564 observations in our data set. Let’s check the total number of missing date data left.

publishedDate_group <- publishedDate_allowed %>%

#The title, author and genre of the book
theBook <- publishedDate_allowed %>% 
  filter(publishedDate == "1900-01-01") %>% 
  select(asin, title, author, category_name, publishedDate)
theBook

A Google search revealed that this book was first published in 1982-01-01, see Goodreads. A check on a few books shows that their dates are correct. so, we’ll change the 1900-01-01 to 1982-01-01.

#Let's change the date 1900-01-01 to 1982-01-01
publishedDate_allowed["publishedDate"][publishedDate_allowed["publishedDate"] == 
                                         "1900-01-01"] <- 1982-01-01
salesData_rev["publishedDate"][salesData_rev["publishedDate"] == 
                                 "1900-01-01"] <- 1982-01-01
#Check to be sure the value has been replaced
head(subset(salesData_rev, publishedDate == "1900-01-01"))

Let’s now generate random date between 1942-02-01 and 2023-10-01, and use them to replace the missing values.

#Let's generate a random date between 2023-10-01 and 1942-02-01
#1. Check min date in date column after removing 1900-01-01
print(min(publishedDate_allowed$publishedDate))
## [1] "1942-02-01"
#2. Replace 0001-01-01 with NA to account for missing values
salesData_rev["publishedDate"][salesData_rev["publishedDate"] == 
                                "0001-01-01"] <- NA
#3. Count the number of missing values to be sure is 45764
print(sum(is.na(salesData_rev$publishedDate)))
## [1] 45764
#4. Generate 45764 random dates
set.seed(45001) #setting a seed to ensure the dates are reproducible
rd_dates <- as.Date(runif(45764, as.Date(1942-02-01),
                          as.Date(2023-10-01))) #generate the random dates
head(rd_dates)
## [1] "1975-05-28" "1975-07-02" "1975-06-01" "1975-05-08" "1975-06-26"
## [6] "1975-05-30"
#5. Replace the missing dates with the random dates
salesData_rev$publishedDate[is.na(salesData_rev$publishedDate)] <- rd_dates
#Check to be sure that values have been replaced
head(subset(salesData_rev, publishedDate == "0001-01-01"))

We are done with our missing values.

Correlations among Variables

So far we’ve completed our exploration. Before I create a dashboard to derive insights from the data, lets check for statistical relationships. To achieve this, we use correlation matrix and coefficients.

#Creating a correlation matrix with discrete variables
#1. Select only numeric variables
salesData_Num <- salesData_rev %>% 
  select_if(., is.numeric) %>% 
  select(stars, reviews, price, category_id)
#2. Create the correlation matrix, rounding up to 4 decimal places
corMatrix <- round(cor(salesData_Num, use = "complete.obs"),4)
corMatrix[upper.tri(corMatrix)] <- NA
corMatrix
##               stars reviews   price category_id
## stars        1.0000      NA      NA          NA
## reviews      0.0306  1.0000      NA          NA
## price       -0.1278 -0.0495  1.0000          NA
## category_id  0.0259 -0.0482 -0.0812           1
#3. Create a heatmap of the correlation matrix
corrplot(corMatrix, method = "color", type = "lower")

The correlation matrix shows that non of the variables are correlated. Thus, we can use these variables on multiple linear regression to predict price. This is because there’ll be no trace of multicollinearity.

Building a price prediction model

Let us finally build a model to predict the price of a book based on book genre and ratings. Book genre is represented by the category_id, and book ratings are determined by stars and reviews.

Therefore, our model is given by:

\(Price = a + stars + reviews + category_id + u\)

#Creating a multiple regression model to predict price
priceModel <- lm(price ~ stars + reviews + category_id, salesData_Num)
#Display the results
summary(priceModel)
##

Using the Data to Answer Questions

Let’s focus on answering questions derived from the data.

Who are the most popular authors?

To answer this question we use hindex. Here we consider the number of books published by each author and the total number of reviews. To consolidate on it, we also look at the average rating of each author. For the purpose of this report, we’ll consider authors that published 100 or more books, has average rating of 4.0, and at least 50000 reviews as the most popular authors. Let’s capture this in our code below.

#Identifying popular authors
popularAuthor <- salesData_rev %>% 
  group_by(author) %>% 
  select(author, stars, reviews) %>% 
  reframe(count = n(), stars = mean(stars), reviews = sum(reviews))
head(popularAuthor)
#Select the most popular authors from popularauthors
mostPopularAthors <- popularAuthor %>% 
  filter(count >= 100 & stars >= 4.0 & reviews >= 50000)
head(mostPopularAthors)

From the above result, only 3 authors made the list. We can increase the list by adjusting any of the conditions above.

Does kindle unlimited affect book sales and popularity?

Here, we’ll look at total book sales categorized as kindle unlimited and non. As a measure of popularity, we’ll use total reviews and average rating. So, we’ll consider which of the two categories has higher sales, higher average ratings and higher total reviews.

First, let’s select only discrete columns grouped by title so we can get the book sales column.

#Group all discrete variables together by the book title
myBooks <- salesData_rev %>% 
  group_by(title) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), price = mean(price), category_id = max(category_id), 
            stars = mean(stars), reviews = sum(reviews), 
            .groups = "drop")
#Add a calculated column for book sales
myBooks <- myBooks %>% 
  mutate(BookSales = count * price)
head(myBooks)

Let’s now join the remaining columns that we need for the analysis. First, we select the relevant columns for the analysis, and join it with myBooks table.

#Impact of kindle unlimited on sales
BookSalesAdded <- salesData_rev %>% 
  select(title, isKindleUnlimited, isBestSeller, isGoodReadsChoice,
         isEditorsPick, category_name, publishedDate)
#Join with myBooks
BookSalesAdded <-  left_join(myBooks, BookSalesAdded, by = "title",
            multiple = "any", unmatched = "drop")
head(BookSalesAdded)

Let’s now compute the impact of kindle unlimited on sales.

#KindleUnlimited impact on book sales
kindleUnlimitedImpact <- BookSalesAdded %>% 
  group_by(isKindleUnlimited) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), BookSales = sum(BookSales),
            stars = mean(stars), reviews = sum(reviews))
head(kindleUnlimitedImpact)

The chart is displayed below:

#Plot the graph
ggplot(kindleUnlimitedImpact, aes(isKindleUnlimited)) +
  geom_bar(aes(weight = BookSales)) +
  labs(title = "Impact of Kindle Unlimited on Book Sales",
       x = "Is Kindle Unlimited",
       y = "Book Sales")

From the above chart, we can say that kindle unlimited does not have notable impact on book sales.

#Best seller impact on book sales
bestSellerImpact <- BookSalesAdded %>%

Are there patterns and seasonality in book publications?

Here we need a line chart, however, we had to summarize the No. of books published per year using the SUM function. So, for each year, we had the total No. of books, and we plotted these totals in a line chart.

#Uncovering patterns and seasonality
#1. Let's split the date column into day, month and year
BookSalesAdded <- BookSalesAdded %>% 
  mutate(day = day(publishedDate),
         month = month(publishedDate),
         year = year(publishedDate)
  )
#2.Sum the number of books published per year. This gives us 
# Total No. of books published each year from 1942 till 2023
timeSeriesData <- BookSalesAdded %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(Books = sum(count)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Books))
head(timeSeriesData)
#3. Plot the time series chart
ggplot(timeSeriesData, aes(x = year, y = Books )) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "No. of Kindle Books Published Over Time",
       x = "Year Published",
       y = "No. of Books Published") +
  theme_minimal()

From the above chart, we observed no particular pattern. But from 2011, the total number of book publications started rising consistently. Please, neglect the spike between 1975 and 1978. These years represent the randomly generated years.

Which is the most popular book genre?

Finally, we calculate total sales per book category and use a bar chart to show which category has more sales. For popularity we compute average ratings and total reviews per category.

#Book sales per category
bookSalesCat <- BookSalesAdded %>% 
  group_by(category_name) %>% 
  summarise(TotalSales = sum(BookSales), stars = mean(stars), 
            reviews = sum(reviews)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(TotalSales))
head(bookSalesCat)
#Draw a column chart for clearer understanding
ggplot(bookSalesCat, aes(category_name)) +
  geom_bar(aes(weight = TotalSales, color = stars )) +
  labs(title = "Book Sales By category",
       x = "Book Genre",
       y = "Book Sales") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal()

From the above, Law, and Science & Math have the most books sold.

Predicting Book Sales

Our final analysis is to create book sales predictive model using multiple regression analysis.

From our data, a lot of variables could affect book sales. They include: price, category, rating, reviews, soldby, kindle unlimited, editor’s pick, good reads choice, and best seller.

We have data for each of these variables, but we cannot use soldby since it is of string data type, and we cannot easily one hot encode the variable.

For the our Boolean or categorical variables, we’ll use one hot encoding to assign 1 for TRUE and 0 for FALSE. Let’s quickly apply this for isKindleUnlimite, IsEditorsPick, IsBestSeller, and IsGoodReadsChoice.

So, our regression model will look thus:

\(BookSales = Const. + Price + stars + reviews + category_id + isKindleUnlimited + isBestSeller + isGoodReadsChoice + isEditorsPick + u\)

#Predicting book sales
#1. One hot encoding isKindleUnlimite, 
#IsEditorsPick, IsBestSeller, and IsGoodReadsChoice variables
#Duplicate the table
PredictionData <- BookSalesAdded
#One hot code the variables
PredictionData <- PredictionData %>% 
  mutate(
    isBestSeller = as.integer(isBestSeller),
    isEditorsPick = as.integer(isEditorsPick),
    isGoodReadsChoice = as.integer(isGoodReadsChoice),
    isKindleUnlimited = as.integer(isKindleUnlimited)
  )
head(PredictionData)

The conversion has successfully been made. Next, we run the correlation matrix with all 8 variables.

#Correlation matrix with discrete variables only
#1. Select only numeric variables
PredictionData <- PredictionData %>% 
  select_if(., is.numeric) %>% 
  select(BookSales, price, stars, reviews, category_id, isKindleUnlimited,
         isBestSeller, isEditorsPick, isGoodReadsChoice)
#2. The correlation matrix, rounding up to 5 decimal places
bookPredMatrix <- round(cor(PredictionData, use = "complete.obs"),5)
bookPredMatrix[upper.tri(corMatrix)] <- 0
bookPredMatrix

#The multiple regression model to predict book sales
BookSalesPredModel <- lm(BookSales ~ price + stars + reviews + category_id + 
                        isKindleUnlimited + isBestSeller + isGoodReadsChoice +
                        isEditorsPick, PredictionData)

#Display the results using stargazer package to create a summary table
